The three fitted $J_5$ central values cluster around
$\bar{\Theta}_{\text{eff}} = 596$\,K. The sample-to-sample standard deviation
of the three central values is approximately $14$\,K, smaller than the
individual bootstrap uncertainties, supporting the stability of
$\Theta_{\text{eff}}$ across samples. We therefore quote
$\Theta_{\text{eff}} = 596 \pm 88$\,K, where the uncertainty represents
a typical bootstrap fit uncertainty.

Information criteria such as AICc and BIC do not decisively distinguish the
single-mode and $J_5$ models because they have the same number of adjustable
parameters and nearly identical residuals. The preference for $J_5$ is
therefore physical rather than purely statistical: the single-mode fit requires
an effective frequency above the one-phonon diamond optical scale, whereas
$J_5$ yields a physically interpretable effective cutoff.

