\subsection{Consistency with Lin et al. (2021)}

For the Lin et al.\ dataset (300--600\,K), the $J_5$ model yields
$R^2 = 0.9777$ with $\Theta_{\text{eff}}$ approaching the upper bound of
3000\,K. The narrow temperature window does not provide sufficient leverage
to constrain $\Theta_{\text{eff}}$.

Lin \textit{et al.}\ also identified quasilocalized phonon contributions near
$68.2(17)$\,meV and $167(12)$\,meV~\cite{Lin2023}. The fitted value
$\Theta_{\text{eff}} = 596\pm88$\,K corresponds to $51\pm8$\,meV, below but
of the same order as the lower quasilocalized scale. This supports interpreting
$\Theta_{\text{eff}}$ not as a single resolved local mode, but as an effective
low-energy spectral scale summarizing acoustic and quasilocalized contributions.

\subsection{Barbosa et al. (2024)}

The Barbosa nanodiamond data are too narrow in temperature range to
discriminate between models. They are included only as qualitative evidence
that multiple relaxation channels can coexist in nanodiamond environments.

