\section{Discussion}

\subsection{Why a Single Mode Suffices for $D(T)$ but Not for $T_1(T)$}

$D(T)$ measures a thermally averaged static shift, sensitive to the mean
square lattice displacement $\langle \hat{u}^2 \rangle_T$. A single effective
phonon mode captures the dominant temperature dependence of this average,
as demonstrated in Paper~I ($R^2 = 0.999946$). In contrast, $T_1(T)$ measures
a dynamic transition rate requiring phonon pairs satisfying the spin-flip
resonance condition $|\omega_1 - \omega_2| \approx \omega_s$. A single
perfectly sharp mode cannot provide the continuum of near-degenerate phonon
pairs with the required frequency differences. A continuum, or at least a
broadened set of modes, is required for an efficient Raman relaxation channel.

\subsection{Why $J_5$ Succeeds Physically Despite Similar $R^2$}

The preference for $J_5$ is physical rather than purely statistical: the
single-mode fit requires $\omega \sim 1800$\,cm$^{-1}$, exceeding the
optical-phonon scale of diamond ($\sim 1332$\,cm$^{-1}$), whereas $J_5$
yields $\Theta_{\text{eff}} \approx 600$\,K, physically interpretable as an
effective low-energy phonon cutoff.

\subsection{Relation to Orbach and Local-Mode Processes}

The minimal $J_5$ model should not be viewed as excluding Orbach or
local-mode processes. Jarmola \textit{et al.}\ identified an activated
contribution with energy scale of order tens of meV~\cite{Jarmola2012}. Over a
restricted temperature window, the $J_5$ transport integral may effectively
reproduce part of the curvature that microscopic analyses attribute to
thermally activated channels. A decisive separation of Raman and Orbach
mechanisms requires fitting a combined model,
\begin{equation}
    \frac{1}{T_1(T)} = \Gamma_0
    + \frac{A_{\text{Orb}}}{e^{\Delta/k_BT}-1}
    + R\!\left(\frac{T}{\Theta_{\text{eff}}}\right)^5
      J_5\!\left(\frac{\Theta_{\text{eff}}}{T}\right).
\end{equation}
Testing this combined model against wide-range data will determine whether
$\Theta_{\text{eff}}$ remains stable when the Orbach channel is resolved
explicitly.

\subsection{How $\coth = 2n+1$ Unifies the Three Phenomena}

The identity $\coth(x) = 2n(x)+1$ is the central link:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{$D(T)$ (Paper~I):} governed by $n(\tilde{\nu}, T)$ (mean occupation).
    \item \textbf{$\Gamma_\phi(T)$ (testable ansatz):} governed by $\coth(\tilde{\nu}_\phi, T) = 2n+1$ (variance).
    \item \textbf{$1/T_1(T)$ (this work):} governed by $n(\omega)[n(\omega)+1]$, integrated
    over the phonon continuum via $J_5$.
\end{itemize}
All three expressions emerge from the same Bose-Einstein statistics but probe
different moments of the phonon displacement distribution. The effective energy
scales $\tilde{\nu}$, $\tilde{\nu}_\phi$, and $\Theta_{\text{eff}}$ need not
be identical, because each phenomenon may couple to a different subset of the
phonon spectrum.

\subsection{Limitations and Outlook}

The present work provides a compact effective framework connecting thermal
shifts, dephasing, and relaxation within a common phonon-occupation language.
Several extensions are deferred to future work:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Joint fit.} A joint fit of $D(T)$, $T_1(T)$, and $T_2(T)$ with
    shared phonon parameters would provide the strongest test of the unified
    DTQEM framework.
    \item \textbf{Orbach contribution.} Testing the combined Raman+Orbach model
    against wide-range data will determine whether $\Theta_{\text{eff}}$ remains
    stable when the Orbach channel is resolved explicitly.
    \item \textbf{Isotopic mass scaling.} DTQEM predicts
    $\tilde{\nu} \propto 1/\sqrt{\mu}$. Measurements on isotopically purified
    $^{12}$C diamond would test this prediction.
    \item \textbf{Extension to other defects.} The $J_5$ transport integral
    applies to any spin system with second-order Raman coupling in a Debye
    medium.
\end{enumerate}

% =============================================================================
% 5. CONCLUSION
% =============================================================================
\section{Conclusion}

We have extended the DTQEM framework from the static zero-field splitting
$D(T)$ to the dynamic spin-lattice relaxation rate $T_1(T)$ and proposed a
corresponding fluctuation ansatz for pure dephasing $\Gamma_\phi(T)$. The
single-mode picture that succeeds for $D(T)$ fails for $T_1(T)$ because of
a fundamental $T^2$ ceiling. The effective Debye--Raman transport integral
$J_5(\Theta_{\text{eff}}/T)$ overcomes this limitation while preserving the
Bose-Einstein foundation of DTQEM, yielding $\Theta_{\text{eff}} = 596 \pm 88$\,K
consistent across three Jarmola ensemble samples. A combined Raman+Orbach
model is proposed for future wide-range validation. The identity
$\coth = 2n+1$ unifies static shifts, dephasing fluctuations, and dynamic
relaxation within a single thermal framework. This compact, physically
interpretable description paves the way for predictive engineering of
NV-based quantum sensors at elevated temperatures.

